Unfortunately, this doesn't appear to work if you are trying to apply the `[JsonConverter]` to an `Enum` type, then have that type used in a collection that is a member of another class. At least not using `System.Text.Json` version `9.0.3`. Here's the basic setup:

```csharp
[JsonConverter(typeof(MyEnumConverter))]
public enum MyEnum {
  [Display(Name = "a")]
  Value1,
  [Display(Name = "b")]
  Value2,
  [Display(Name = "c")]
  Value3
}
public record MyDto(
  IEnumerable<MyEnum> Options,
  MyEnum DefaultOption
);
```

If I have a custom converter that uses the `[Display]` attributes to determine the string representation of the enum values, an instance of `MyDto` constructed as `new MyDto([MyEnum.Value1,MyEnum.Value2], MyEnum.Value1)` will, in the absence of any other configuration, serialize to `{"Options":[1,2],"DefaultOption":1}` even though it should be `{"Options":["a","b"],"DefaultOption":"a"}` (implementation below). The behavior does not change whether the converter is added to the `JsonSerializerOptions.Converters`, set using the attribute, or both.

Interestingly enough, this all works much better on the deserialization side of things, though not perfectly. If you have `{"Options":["a","b"],"DefaultOption":"a"}` and add the custom converter to `JsonSerializerOptions.Converters`, this deserializes just fine. Using the attribute in this scenario seems to have no effect whatsoever.

Here is the converter code:

```csharp
public class JsonNameEnumConverter : JsonConverter<MyEnum> {

    private static Dictionary<string, MyEnum> NameValueMap { get; } = typeof(MyEnum)
        .GetFields(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Static)
        .Select(m => KeyValuePair.Create(m.GetCustomAttribute<DisplayAttribute>()?.Name ?? m.Name, Enum.Parse<MyEnum>(m.Name)))
        .ToDictionary();

    private static Dictionary<MyEnum, string> ValueNameMap { get; } = typeof(MyEnum)
        .GetFields(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Static)
        .Select(m => KeyValuePair.Create(Enum.Parse<MyEnum>(m.Name), m.GetCustomAttribute<DisplayAttribute>()?.Name ?? m.Name))
        .ToDictionary();

    public override MyEnum Read(ref Utf8JsonReader reader, Type typeToConvert, JsonSerializerOptions options) =>
        NameValueMap[reader.GetString() ?? string.Empty];

    public override void Write(Utf8JsonWriter writer, MyEnum value, JsonSerializerOptions options) =>
        writer.WriteStringValue(ValueNameMap[value]);
}
```

Could this be solved by adding a `TargetType` to the `JsonConverterAttribute`? That way you can target multiple different types too. Now the example would look like:

```csharp
public class Model
{
    [JsonConverter(typeof(JsonStringEnumConverter), TargetType = typeof(Day))]
