### Background and motivation

I have an application that transforms huge amounts of data on low-memory environment. The data is delivered from external service in a format that cannot be changed:
```csharp
class DataFile
{
  public MetadataClass Metadata { get; set }
  public IEnumerable<DataItem> DataList { get; set }
}
```
Due to current constraints of System.Text.Json, the DataList is materialized immediately (as it is a nested Enumerable). After data is deserialized, it takes over 3GB of 8GB available memory, but quite often it just throws an OutOfMemory exception on (internal) List<DataItem> resize

I'd like to specify an initial capacity of the deserialized Enumerable to avoid memory reallocations. My current alternatives are: (1) increase memory available (2) prepare a custom JsonConverter based on LinkedList<> (my current solution)

### API Proposal

// new class
```csharp
namespace System.Text.Json.Serialization.Attributes;

public class JsonCollectionCapacityAttribute : JsonAttribute
{
    public JsonCollectionCapacityAttribute (int capacity) => Capacity = capacity

    public int Capacity { get; }
}
```

// in IEnumerableOfTConverter.cs
```csharp
protected override void CreateCollection(ref Utf8JsonReader reader, scoped ref ReadStack state, JsonSerializerOptions options)
{
    if (!_isDeserializable)
    {
        ThrowHelper.ThrowNotSupportedException_CannotPopulateCollection(Type, ref reader, ref state);
    }


    var collectionCapacityAttribute = state.ParentProperty.AttributeProvider.GetCustomAttributes(typeof(JsonCollectionCapacityAttribute), false).FirstOrDefault();

    state.Current.ReturnValue = collectionCapacityAttribute is null ? new List<TElement>() : new List<TElement>(collectionCapacityAttribute.Capacity);
}
```

// in IAsyncEnumerableOfTConverter.cs
```csharp
protected override void CreateCollection(ref Utf8JsonReader reader, scoped ref ReadStack state, JsonSerializerOptions options)
{
    var collectionCapacityAttribute = state.ParentProperty.AttributeProvider.GetCustomAttributes(typeof(JsonCollectionCapacityAttribute), false).FirstOrDefault();

    state.Current.ReturnValue = collectionCapacityAttribute is null ? new BufferedAsyncEnumerable() : new BufferedAsyncEnumerable(collectionCapacityAttribute.Capacity);
}
```

### API Usage

```csharp
class DataFile
{
  public MetadataClass Metadata { get; set }

  [JsonCollectionCapacity(1000000)]
  public IEnumerable<DataItem> DataList { get; set }
}
```


### Alternative Designs

_No response_

### Risks

_No response_

