Sorry @gregsdennis, I meant serialization as you assumed.  While you're technically 100% correct, I was hoping to not have to have another object.  This is already a temporary object that's populated via AutoMapper and ProjectTo.  While I don't want the caller to get the value, I do need it for the next query that's done in the same method.  

I was hoping to avoid having to do yet another mapping to strip out that one property.

Think of something like this obviously non-compiling code.  Need the internal ID for the next query but don't want to send it back.

```csharp
var items = await _context.SomeTable.ProjectTo<SomeObj>(...).ToArrayAsync();
var ids = items.Select(x => x.InternalIdentifier).ToArrayAsync();
var otherStuff = await _context.SomeOtherTable
    .Where(x => ids.Contains(x.SomeTableIdentifier))
    .ToArrayAsync();

var mapping = otherStuff
    .ToLookup(x => x.InternalIdentifier)
    .ToDictionary(x => x.Key, x => x.Select(...));

foreach (var item in items) {
    item.Stuff = mapping[item.InternalIdentifier];
```

I see you mention attribute resolution of virtual properties, I assume this is the same problem I'm seeing when I'm doing this:

```
using System;
using System.Text.Json;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization;

public static class test
{
    [JsonPolymorphic(UnknownDerivedTypeHandling = JsonUnknownDerivedTypeHandling.FallBackToNearestAncestor, TypeDiscriminatorPropertyName = "action")]
    [JsonDerivedType(typeof(inherited), nameof(anEnum.attribute3))]
    public class root
    {
        [JsonConverter(typeof(JsonStringEnumConverter))]
        public anEnum action { get; set; }
        [JsonConverter(typeof(JsonStringEnumConverter))]
        public anEnum action2 { get; set; }
    }

    public class inherited : root
    {
        public string asdf { get; set; }
        public string asdf2 { get; set; }
    }

    public enum anEnum
    {
        attribute1,
        attribute2,
        attribute3,
        attribute4
    }

    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        inherited input = new()
        {
            action = anEnum.attribute3,
            action2 = anEnum.attribute2,
            asdf = "asdf1",
            asdf2 = "asdf2",
        };
        Console.WriteLine(JsonSerializer.Serialize(input));
        Console.WriteLine(JsonSerializer.Serialize((root)input));
    }
}

```
The output I get is the following:

```
    {"asdf":"asdf1","asdf2":"asdf2","action":"attribute1","action2":"attribute2"}
    {"action":"attribute4","asdf":"asdf1","asdf2":"asdf2","action":"attribute1","action2":"attribute2"}
```

If I remove the jsonpolymorphic tag, and run the same code, I get the following:

```
{"asdf":"asdf1","asdf2":"asdf2","action":"attribute3","action2":"attribute2"}
{"$type":"attribute4","asdf":"asdf1","asdf2":"asdf2","action":"attribute3","action2":"attribute2"}
```

So, the first line is serialized directly from the actual instantiated class (i.e. instanced, in this case), the second is when it's serialized via the root baseclass, i.e. I assume we're seeing the actually derived object, and I assume the first property is a virtual property that in the polymorphed instance has its name overridden by the polymorphism typediscriminatorpropertyname attribute, while in the non-polymorphed instance the virtual property is just named $type.

When I deserialize it again, everything looks fine, it's only when I try to f.ex send it over the wire by serializing it via the base class that it actually turns into a problem.

here is another variation that the [workarounds](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/92780#issuecomment-1739770632) mentioned above **does not** work for.

```csharp
using System.Text.Json;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization;

var json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new CustomerLimitTransactionLogRequest { AccountNumber = "1234567890" });

Console.WriteLine($"Json Data: {json}");

public abstract class BaseCustomerLimitRequest
{
    public virtual string? AccountNumber { get; set; }
}

public class CustomerLimitTransactionLogRequest : BaseCustomerLimitRequest
{
    [JsonPropertyName("accountNo")]
    public override string? AccountNumber { get; set; }
}
```

body:
### Background and motivation

I am working with a web API that returns a paginated response. I'd like to deserialize the content of the `page` property into an `IAsyncEnumerable<T>` but I can't because it is not the root-level object. I can ignore the other members (in this example, `etag`).

```json
{
  "page": [
    { "name": "item1" },
    { "name": "item2" }
  ],
  "etag": "0000000"
}
```

### API Proposal

```csharp
namespace System.Text.Json;

partial class JsonSerializer
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Deserializes a member of a json content stream into an <see cref="IAsyncEnumerable{T}"/>,
    /// ignoring all other members of the root element. <paramref name="jsonPath"/> must refer to
    /// a json array member.
    /// </summary>
    public IAsyncEnumerable<T> DeserializeAsyncEnumerableMember<T>(
      Stream stream,
      JsonPath jsonPath,
      JsonSerializerOptions jsonOptions,
      CancellationToken cancellationToken
    );
}

/// <summary>
/// API for strongly-typed json path specification.
/// </summary>
/// <remarks>
/// Avoids requiring the caller to memorize the json path semantics
/// </remarks>
public readonly struct JsonPath : ISpanParsable<JsonPath> {
    /// <summary>Creates a new path representing a child node of the current object with the given index.</summary>
    public JsonPath Index(int index);

    /// <summary>Creates a new path representing a child node of the current object with the given property name.</summary>
    public JsonPath Property(string propertyName);

    /// <summary>The root-level object reference.</summary>
    public static JsonPath Root { get; }

  /// <summary>Produces a well-formed json path, such as "$.item[0].child.foo"</summary>
  public override string ToString();
}
```


### API Usage

```csharp
var client = new HttpClient();
var response = await client.GetAsync(
    "https://some.api/data?page=6",
    HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead,
    cancellationToken
    );

response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();

var nextPageUri = response.Headers.GetValues("X-Next-Page").Single();

await var stream = response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync(cancellationToken);

var data = JsonSerializer.DeserializeAsyncEnumerableMember<SomeApiData>(
    stream,
    JsonPath.Root.Property("data"),
    JsonSerializerOptions.Default,
    cancelaltionToken
    );

await foreach (var item in data) {
    yield return item;
}
```


### Alternative Designs

Consider using `string` instead of introducing a `JsonPath` API. This may be more performant or allocate less, but may require higher burden on the user and higher chance of runtime failure by providing the wrong json path format.

### Risks

_No response_

