### Description

When serializing with options ```ReferenceHandler.IgnoreCycles``` enabled, looping references will be serialized as null.

### Reproduction Steps

Creating a class structure as shown below and serializing it with ReferenceHandler.IgnoreCycles, produces the following json:

```json
{
    "Nested": {
        "Samples": [
            null
        ]
    }
}
```

```csharp
public class Sample
{
    public virtual Nested Nested { get; set; }
}
public class Nested
{
    public virtual IEnumerable<Sample> Samples { get; set; }
}

var sample = new Sample();
var association = new Nested
{
    Samples = new List<Sample> { sample }
};
sample.Nested = association;

var json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(sample, new JsonSerializerOptions { ReferenceHandler = ReferenceHandler.IgnoreCycles });

```

Even, if adding ```JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenWritingNull```, it will still write the null element in the list.










### Expected behavior

I would expect the json to be serialized as shown below:

```json
{
    "Nested": {
        "Samples": [
        ]
    }
}
```

### Actual behavior

The json looks like below, having inserted a null element in the list.

```json
{
    "Nested": {
        "Samples": [
            null
        ]
    }
}
```

### Regression?

_No response_

### Known Workarounds

_No response_

### Configuration

_No response_

### Other information

I discovered the problem when using EntityFramework. If having query with includes, then serializing that model to json and deserializing it back into the model and finally execute and Update in EF. That causes EF to believe there is an element in the list, an  a ```NullReferenceException``` is thrown.

