If for whatever reason Vogen does not allow you to create partial class stubs for the JsonConverters it generates, or you simply don't like creating such stubs, there is another alternative workaround.

Instead of using the `SourceGenerationContext.Default` and the `[JsonSourceGenerationOptions]` for the (de)serialization settings, you can create a `SourceGenerationContext` instance with a `JsonSerializerOptions` instance (thus not requiring the STJ source generator to see/inspect the JsonConverter types) in a similar manner to this:

```C#
[JsonSourceGenerationOptions(GenerationMode = JsonSourceGenerationMode.Default)]
[JsonSerializable(typeof(AccountMembership))]
[JsonSerializable(typeof(AccountId))]
public partial class SourceGenerationContext : JsonSerializerContext
{
    //
    // Use this instead of the Default property
    //
    public static SourceGenerationContext UseThis {get; } = CreateMyContextWithOptions();

    private static SourceGenerationContext CreateMyContextWithOptions()
    {
        var opts = new JsonSerializerOptions
        {
            DefaultIgnoreCondition = JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenWritingNull
        };

        opts.Converters.Add(new AccountId.AccountIdSystemTextJsonConverter());
        return new SourceGenerationContext(opts);
    }
}
```

I see, so this is the chicken before the egg type of scenario. Where the source generators are not aware of the source created by other generators at the type of generation? Even if I was able to create a partial class in my own code, I do not think the source generator would be able to see that it is inherited from JsonConverter, as the inheritance is added via the source generator.

How about doing something like this then, where you add a JsonSourceGenerationOptionsConverter attribute to the JsonSerializerContext. Then the source generator looks for those attributes added to the class and use them to populate the Converters.

```c#
[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Class, AllowMultiple = true, Inherited = false)]
public class JsonSourceGenerationOptionsConverterAttribute<T> : System.Attribute where T : JsonConverter
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Constructs a new <see cref="JsonSourceGenearationConverterOptionsAttribute{T}"/> instance.
    /// </summary>
    public JsonSourceGenerationOptionsConverterAttribute() { }

    /// <summary>
    /// Gets the type of the converter.
    /// </summary>
    public Type ConverterType => typeof(T);
}

[JsonSourceGenerationOptions(
    GenerationMode = JsonSourceGenerationMode.Default,
    DefaultIgnoreCondition = JsonIgnoreCondition.WhenWritingNull,
    UnknownTypeHandling = JsonUnknownTypeHandling.JsonNode)]
[JsonSerializable(typeof(AccountMembership))]
[JsonSerializable(typeof(AccountId))]
[JsonSourceGenerationOptionsConverter<AccountId.AccountIdSystemTextJsonConverter>()]
public partial class SourceGenerationContext : JsonSerializerContext
{
}
```

